    <node id=", which does make it more complex. But I just wanted to say that I think that youth work has perhaps not have the recognition that it's needed and yesterday was a positive step.&#10;Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Okay, thank you. We've got some questions now on early help and enhanced support from Janet Finch-Saunders.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. Good morning. In terms of local primary mental health support services, what is your understanding of the issues leading to some health boards not meeting the Mental Health (Wales) Measure 2010 targets for assessment and therapy for children and young people, and how much of this is due to an increase in demand?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Yes, thanks very much. So, it's important to say, I think, at the outset, just by way of reminder, that the target, quite rightly, changed for children and young people. The target changed some years ago for adults, so it was only right that there was an equalisation around children. So, the services were working, a couple of years ago, with significant demand and then a change in the standard. I think you're absolutely right;" />
    <node id=" The second one is to develop the ingredients for successful working in this area, and then, thirdly, to determine or propose priorities and sequencing of next steps. So, that's the next stage of that. I'm pretty sure we'll come on shortly—or hopefully—to the potential of the regional partnership boards. There is some work that we are doing as a programme with the children's commissioner in terms of working more with the regional partnership boards in taking forward this work. So, that will run alongside. But during the summer, then, we will be developing that framework approach, and we will be participating in the Association of Directors of Social Services conference in September, and then a follow-up workshop in October on this matter. On your question of 'Well, what happens after the programme?' we are currently working on legacy arrangements for the programme. I'm pretty secure on the specialist CAMHS element. That will move, most likely, to the CAMHS network, which is part of the NHS mental health network. I actually chair the mental health network and that's one part of that. The whole-school approach element is already settled in Government and we've got a connection in to that. The question that's outstanding is where the early help and enhanced support and" />
    <node id="To develop a more fluid and integrated health and social care system in Wales, with increased access to psychological therapies and cross-sector roles within the next five to ten years, several steps can be taken:&#10;&#10;1. Encourage collaboration between sectors: This involves facilitating discussions and agreements on integrating services, such as placing psychologists in social care units, as mentioned in the transcript. It is crucial to ensure an appetite for change and a recognized need for better access to psychological therapies.&#10;&#10;2. Address challenges head-on: Acknowledge potential difficulties in implementing cross-sector roles and integrated services. These challenges may include differences in professional cultures, training requirements, or resistance to change. By addressing these concerns openly, stakeholders can work together to find solutions.&#10;&#10;3. Implement the Matrics Cymru framework: This framework focuses on children and young people's psychological therapies. Ensuring its development and implementation will help create a more cohesive mental health care system for this demographic.&#10;&#10;4. Invest in staff retention and well-being: To maintain a capable workforce, focus on factors affecting staff retention, such as well-being at work, teamwork, organizational culture, training opportunities, and career development. This investment will help create a more stable and motivated workforce capable of managing the increased demands of an integrated health and social care system.&#10;&#10;5. Utilize communities of practice: These groups bring together professionals to share knowledge, conduct collective audits, reflect on service improvements, and learn from one another. By fostering a culture of continuous learning and collaboration, Wales can develop a more integrated health and social care system.&#10;&#10;6. Improve transitions between services: Aim to minimize the number of transitions for individuals accessing mental health services. This will require clear communication, coordination, and cooperation between different sectors and service providers.&#10;&#10;Challenges that may arise in this effort include:&#10;&#10;1. Resistance to change: Professionals may resist changes to their roles or the systems they work within. Addressing this resistance requires effective communication, transparency about the reasons for change, and involvement of stakeholders in the decision-making process.&#10;&#10;2. Resource allocation: Integrating health and social care services may require additional funding, which can be a challenge to secure. It is essential to make a strong case for the benefits of integration and demonstrate the potential return on investment in terms of improved patient outcomes and reduced costs in the long term.&#10;&#10;3. Balancing the whole-system approach: Ensuring that all areas of the system are in balance and progressing together can be difficult, as imbalances may jeopardize progress in other parts of the programme. Regular monitoring and adjustments will be necessary to maintain equilibrium.&#10;&#10;4. Addressing language needs: Ensuring adequate numbers of Welsh-speaking practitioners in areas with high demand for Welsh language services is crucial. This may require targeted recruitment efforts, training programs, or incentives to encourage bilingual professionals to work in these regions." />
    <node id=" doing collective audit, doing collective reflection on service improvement, and being very clear about learning from one another. And, if you're a clinician, that gives you a lot of motivation to keep driving forward. So, I think we have the fundamental building blocks in place, but there is more to do around the environment in which our practitioners and our staff operate.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: What about the Welsh language in the health board?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Thank you very much. There are two elements, if I may, just on that. In your report of last year you highlighted the need to do further work on the use of the Welsh language, and have we got enough Welsh language practitioners where we need them. We are doing that piece of work. I'm pleased to say that, over the last few years, I think all health boards have really stepped up in terms of being able to understand the levels of Welsh speaking amongst employed staff and where their Welsh-speaking communities are. We're particularly looking at it in terms of in-patient CAMHS and community intensive services, because, particularly when people are feeling at their most vulnerable, they would choose the language they wish to choose. So," />
    <node id="1. Reason for increasing trend in neurodevelopmental referrals, particularly autism: There is no clear answer as to why there is an increase in neurodevelopmental referrals, specifically autism, among young children. Research is being conducted to understand the reasons behind this growing trend, but currently, it is not well understood (Carol Shillabeer).&#10;2. Growing demand for speech and language support: There has been a significant rise in autism referrals, with an example of a health board experiencing a growth from 75 to 300 referrals within a year (Carol Shillabeer). This increased demand puts pressure on clinical teams responsible for assessment and support.&#10;&#10;Healthcare system addressing the growing demand:&#10;&#10;1. Establishment of seven neurodevelopmental teams across Wales, introducing a national pathway, and creating a community-of-practice environment to better manage the increase in referrals (Carol Shillabeer).&#10;2. Efforts to understand the long-term trajectory of referrals due to new pathways and increased capacity (Carol Shillabeer).&#10;3. Recognition that many families seeking support do not meet the threshold for a diagnosis, meaning there is still a need for help and resources even if they don't qualify for specific educational support (Hefin David AM).&#10;4. Acknowledgement of the need to address broader needs beyond autism and other neurological conditions, as well as addressing overlapping needs in early help, enhanced support, and learning disability services (Hefin David AM).&#10;5. The Welsh Government has commissioned a piece of work by Patrick Holton to assess the demands on capacity in relation to neurodevelopmental services, aiming for long-term planning in response to the growing trends (Carol Shillabeer)." />
    <node id=" David AM&#10;Content: I think, Chair, I should have declared an interest here, as my daughter has been diagnosed with autism and is currently going through the process of receiving neurodevelopmental speech and language support particularly. We're seeing an increase in neurodevelopmental referrals, and that will increase further in the future. Can you give us an explanation as to why this demand is growing and how we're going to meet capacity to deliver and for support for those children?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Thank you. They're very big questions in terms of 'why'. I'm not sure that anyone really knows why, if I'm honest, although there is a lot of academic research going on. What we do know is that we are starting to see the scale of those referrals coming through. So, in the information provided, I refer to the NHS digital prevalence report in England, which indicates that about 5.5 per cent of two to four-year-olds have a mental disorder. Now, that sounds a bit shocking when we say that, but that's in the international classification scaling, and, of that, certainly, 2.5 per cent is around autism. I can just testify, in real life, that demand is absolutely growing" />
