    <node id="1. Further development work on early help and enhanced support: Both the speakers recognize that there is still significant development work required for early help and enhanced support, which may take another year or 18 months to complete. This suggests that the current program has not yet fully addressed these critical areas, and further efforts are needed.&#10;   &#10;2. Evaluating the current program's effectiveness: While the current Together for Children and Young People program has made progress in certain areas, there have been lulls during its implementation. Given this, it is essential to assess whether extending the current program would be more beneficial or if a new multi-agency effort should take its place.&#10;&#10;3. Maintaining a holistic approach: It is crucial to maintain a comprehensive view of children's mental health by focusing on early help, enhanced support, and youth work. This integrated strategy ensures that all aspects affecting children's mental health are addressed, including interventions at critical stages in their lives.&#10;&#10;4. Role of regional partnership boards: Regional partnership boards play an essential role in facilitating collaboration between local authorities, health boards, and other key partners to effectively plan, commission, and deliver mental health services for children and young people. By working closely with these boards, the Together for Children and Young People program can promote best practices, support resource allocation, and monitor progress towards improving mental health outcomes.&#10;&#10;5. Establishing legacy arrangements: To sustain the gains achieved during the program, clear legacy arrangements must be established. Specialist CAMHS services will likely be integrated into the NHS mental health network, while the whole-school approach element has already been adopted by the government. The challenge lies in determining where early help and enhanced support fit within the system and ensuring a smooth transition for this work stream.&#10;&#10;Given these factors, it may be more appropriate to consider a different multi-agency effort that builds upon the progress made by the Together for Children and Young People program while addressing its identified gaps, particularly in early help and enhanced support. This new initiative should collaborate with regional partnership boards, maintain a holistic approach, and establish clear legacy arrangements to ensure long-term success." />
