    <node id="The workforce profile in Wales is evolving to address recruitment challenges by implementing skill mixing. This approach involves using different types of roles, including those from the third sector, to provide direct front-line service provision. The trend shows a move towards better skill mix, with health boards like Powys Teaching Health Board employing more psychology assistants and other non-traditional professionals.&#10;&#10;The third sector is making significant contributions to service provision in various areas of healthcare services. This involvement is expected to continue and increase due to ongoing recruitment challenges and training time constraints for nursing and other professionals. While there has been an increase in commissioning numbers for nursing and other professionals, the shortage is not a quick fix, as it takes time for new recruits to receive training.&#10;&#10;In response to these challenges, healthcare services are focusing on staff retention, well-being, teamwork, culture of organizations, and career opportunities for healthcare professionals, in addition to traditional training and development efforts. Communities of practice have also become standard across healthcare services, allowing professionals to collaborate, reflect on service improvement, and learn from one another, which supports upskilling and developing the existing workforce by sharing best practices and knowledge.&#10;&#10;In summary, the trend in workforce profile shows a shift towards skill mixing, with the third sector playing an increasingly important role in service provision compared to NHS-employed professionals. This approach is expected to continue as healthcare services address recruitment challenges and focus on staff development and well-being." />
    <node id="❓ Question: How is the Welsh social care system planning to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children within the next five to ten years, including reaching those in foster care with less frequent reviews, and can this be accomplished according to the confidence of Suzy Davies AM and Carol Shillabeer?&#10;&#10;The Welsh social care system plans to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children by focusing on the 'early help and enhanced support' work stream. This initiative will question whether a greater emphasis on emotional health and mental health should be incorporated into the health assessment of young people who are care experienced. Specifically, they aim to ensure that this aspect of support is more prominent and suitable for children with challenging backgrounds that led them to become part of the system.&#10;&#10;This enhanced focus on emotional and mental health assessments will address Suzy Davies AM's concern about reaching children who are being fostered and may not have frequent looked-after children reviews, ensuring that these interventions reach all relevant young people in various situations.&#10;&#10;Carol Shillabeer, as the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, did not explicitly express confidence in the plan but acknowledged the importance of this work and the need for a whole-system approach to children and young people's mental health. The Welsh social care system's top officials recognize the significance of these improvements, and they are working towards making earlier progress on psychological therapies and support for looked-after children.&#10;&#10;Considering the information provided in the transcripts, it is reasonable to suggest that there is a strong commitment from key figures like Suzy Davies AM and Carol Shillabeer to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children within the next five to ten years, including reaching those in foster care with less frequent reviews." />
