    <node id="1. The initial focus of the Together for Children and Young People program was indeed on improving access to specialist Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS). The windscreen model was developed to prioritize this goal and make immediate progress in addressing issues related to access.&#10;2. A red, amber, or green rating system was used to evaluate the program's progress regarding its focus on CAMHS. However, specific details about the ratings are not provided in the transcript. Overall, it is mentioned that progress has been made, but there are still areas where improvements can be made.&#10;3. While the transcript does not provide exact ratings or a comprehensive understanding of the current status regarding CAMHS access improvement, it is clear that the program acknowledges ongoing challenges and remains committed to further progress." />
    <node id="1. Patrick Holton is an individual commissioned by the Welsh Government to conduct a piece of work that aims to provide a more independent view of the long-term trends in demands on capacity related to neurodevelopmental conditions, including autism.&#10;2. This work will help the Welsh Government and relevant authorities understand the potential future demands on capacity and services for neurodevelopmental conditions, enabling them to plan more effectively for the long term, including resource allocation, staffing, and infrastructure development.&#10;3. The report generated by Patrick Holton's work is expected to be available in the coming months, providing valuable insights that will help shape a comprehensive, long-term vision for addressing neurodevelopmental conditions in Wales, ensuring support and resources are available for those who need them over the next several years and beyond." />
    <node id="❓ Question: What measures is the Government taking to support Regional Partnership Boards (RPBs) in their understanding and handling of child and adolescent emotional mental health, and could a mechanism be necessary for guiding this process over the next 12 to 18 months?&#10;&#10;In response to this question, Carol Shillabeer acknowledged that the Government has taken some preparatory steps to support RPBs in addressing child and adolescent emotional mental health. Specifically, she mentioned the inclusion of a reference to child and adolescent emotional mental health in last year's integrated care fund guidance and a recent letter allocating £200,000 per RPB to further support this work.&#10;&#10;Carol Shillabeer also suggested that a mechanism might be needed to guide the process over the next 12 to 18 months, as her sense is that different RPBs are in different stages of readiness for taking on this challenge. She emphasized that they are currently working with the Children's Commissioner to better understand and mirror the RPBs' development and management of children and young people's concerns." />
