    <edge source=" from children into adult services. Now, I know we had the—. The transition guidance was published a couple of years ago now, and the programme was involved in developing that guidance. But what's your assessment of the impact that it's had? Because we clearly are still seeing people falling through the gaps, aren't we?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Yes, thank you for that. You're absolutely right; we developed that guidance and we are currently in the process of the evaluation of that. And, in particular, I know that the children's commissioner is very focused on transition, not just around children in receipt of emotional mental health support, but children in paediatric wards, and there is a working group with Welsh Government looking at this.  The children's commissioner has used our guidance to put that on the table to say, 'Well, if this works, this needs to be considered as a model for using elsewhere'. But the big question there is 'if'. So, we do want to get evaluation. If I were just to give an estimate of where I think this will land, I think it will have made improvements, but there may well be some further work to do in enhancing, supporting, auditing that every child" target="1. The Together for Children and Young People program, established in 2015, has made significant progress, particularly in building fundamental blocks for service improvement, collective audit, reflection, and learning from one another. This assessment comes from Carol Shillabeer, the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, who manages the program.&#10;2. The program has been guided by a report called 'Making Sense' from Hafal, which outlines 10 key asks from young people who had experience with the service. These asks focus on supporting teachers and others at an earlier stage, as well as ensuring that specialist help is available when needed.&#10;3. The program has also been involved in developing transition guidance for children moving from children's to adult services, although there is still work to be done to ensure a smooth transition and prevent young people from falling through the gaps.&#10;4. Additionally, the program aims to create a more integrated and joined-up approach between health and social care for approximately 100 children who have experienced care in multiple settings. This initiative involves bringing together social care and healthcare teams to provide better coordinated services for these vulnerable children, with a meeting scheduled with the Children's Commissioner to discuss next steps.&#10;5. The program intersects with the outcomes for the children in care work programme through cross-links such as having a member of the program board sitting on the outcomes for children ministerial group and having a director of social services on the program board. This ensures that there is clear communication between the two groups to better support vulnerable children and young people in Wales.">
