    <edge source="The integration of psychological therapies into a social care unit in south Wales could lead to more fluid roles moving across sectors, as well as the design of fully integrated services. This is one test of the seamless health and social care system for Wales, with the goal of bringing these sectors together over the next five to ten years. The emphasis on this being a whole-system approach to children and young people's mental health is crucial, as any imbalance in the system could jeopardize progress. Specifically, the programme aims to make earlier progress on psychological therapies, recognizing the need for greater support, particularly for looked-after children who have experienced challenging backgrounds. This focus on emotional health and mental health is a key part of health assessments for these young people. The aim is to ensure that this work reaches children in various situations, including those who are fostered and may not have frequent looked-after children reviews." target="1. Factors contributing to the progress and lull in the Together for Children and Young People program: The progress made in the Together for Children and Young People program can be attributed to a strong start, a change in personnel that gathered momentum over the last year or 18 months, and an increased focus on whole-school approach. However, there was also a lull in the middle of the program, which could be due to various factors such as changes in team dynamics, redirection of resources, or shifting priorities.&#10;2. Importance of focusing on the whole system, including early help, enhanced support, and youth work: It is critical to focus on the whole system for several reasons: a) A holistic approach ensures that all aspects affecting children's mental health are addressed; b) Early help and enhanced support provide interventions at crucial stages in children's lives, reducing the need for more intensive and costly specialist care later; c) Including youth work highlights the importance of non-formal education and recreation in promoting positive mental health outcomes; d) Addressing children's mental health requires a coordinated effort from all stakeholders, including families, schools, healthcare providers, and community organizations.&#10;3. Role of regional partnership boards: Regional partnership boards play an essential role in facilitating collaboration between local authorities, health boards, and other key partners to ensure effective planning, commissioning, and delivery of mental health services for children and young people. By working closely with these boards, the Together for Children and Young People program can promote best practices, support resource allocation, and monitor progress towards improving mental health outcomes.&#10;4. Legacy arrangements: To sustain the gains achieved during the program, it is essential to establish clear legacy arrangements. Specialist CAMHS services will likely be integrated into the NHS mental health network, while the whole-school approach element has already been adopted by the government. The challenge lies in determining where early help and enhanced support fit within the system and ensuring a smooth transition for this work stream.&#10;5. Focus on looked-after children: A significant focus of the program is improving mental health assessments and interventions for looked-after children, including those who are fostered and may not have frequent looked-after children reviews. This includes reviewing current assessment practices and considering whether a greater emphasis on emotional health and mental health should be incorporated into these assessments, as well as ensuring adequate support for these vulnerable young people based on their unique backgrounds and experiences.">
