    <edge source="&#10;Content: They're starting to come together. There is a—graph 13 in terms of the CAMHS profile. Each year we do the NHS benchmarking, and we can see where we are compared to others, and I would expect over the next year or two that we see a bit more narrowing.&#10;Speaker: Hefin David AM&#10;Content: So, if you compare a child in Wales with a child in England in the last two years who's been through this, would they have had a different experience as a result, and different clinical advice as a result, or is there consistency despite the difference in workforce profile?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: That's quite a big question. Hand on heart, could I tell you I absolutely know the detail of that? No, I couldn't. The practice in this area is guided by National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance, so it's pretty much guided. We would expect all of our practitioners to be able to work to NICE guidance. When you skill mix a team, you enable the right referrals to go to the right person, so you wouldn't necessarily have a child or young person with particularly complex needs—well, you would match them to the right practitioner" target="The workforce profile in Wales is evolving to address recruitment challenges by implementing skill mixing. This approach involves using different types of roles, including those from the third sector, to provide direct front-line service provision. The trend shows a move towards better skill mix, with health boards like Powys Teaching Health Board employing more psychology assistants and other non-traditional professionals.&#10;&#10;The third sector is making significant contributions to service provision in various areas of healthcare services. This involvement is expected to continue and increase due to ongoing recruitment challenges and training time constraints for nursing and other professionals. While there has been an increase in commissioning numbers for nursing and other professionals, the shortage is not a quick fix, as it takes time for new recruits to receive training.&#10;&#10;In response to these challenges, healthcare services are focusing on staff retention, well-being, teamwork, culture of organizations, and career opportunities for healthcare professionals, in addition to traditional training and development efforts. Communities of practice have also become standard across healthcare services, allowing professionals to collaborate, reflect on service improvement, and learn from one another, which supports upskilling and developing the existing workforce by sharing best practices and knowledge.&#10;&#10;In summary, the trend in workforce profile shows a shift towards skill mixing, with the third sector playing an increasingly important role in service provision compared to NHS-employed professionals. This approach is expected to continue as healthcare services address recruitment challenges and focus on staff development and well-being.">
