ntal health network, while the whole-school approach element has already been adopted by the government. The challenge lies in determining where early help and enhanced support fit within the system and ensuring a smooth transition for this work stream.&#10;5. Focus on looked-after children: A significant focus of the program is improving mental health assessments and interventions for looked-after children, including those who are fostered and may not have frequent looked-after children reviews. This includes reviewing current assessment practices and considering whether a greater emphasis on emotional health and mental health should be incorporated into these assessments, as well as ensuring adequate support for these vulnerable young people based on their unique backgrounds and experiences." target="❓ Question: What measures is the Government taking to support Regional Partnership Boards (RPBs) in their understanding and handling of child and adolescent emotional mental health, and could a mechanism be necessary for guiding this process over the next 12 to 18 months?&#10;&#10;In response to this question, Carol Shillabeer acknowledged that the Government has taken some preparatory steps to support RPBs in addressing child and adolescent emotional mental health. Specifically, she mentioned the inclusion of a reference to child and adolescent emotional mental health in last year's integrated care fund guidance and a recent letter allocating £200,000 per RPB to further support this work.&#10;&#10;Carol Shillabeer also suggested that a mechanism might be needed to guide the process over the next 12 to 18 months, as her sense is that different RPBs are in different stages of readiness for taking on this challenge. She emphasized that they are currently working with the Children's Commissioner to better understand and mirror the RPBs' development and management of children and young people's concerns.">
