    <edge source="Speaker: Lynne Neagle AM&#10;Content: Good morning, everyone, and welcome to the Children, Young People and Education committee this morning. We've received apologies for absence from Siân Gwenllian and there is no substitute this morning. Can I ask if Members have got any declarations of interest they'd like to make, please? No? Okay. Thank you. Item 2 this morning, then, is a further session on our follow-up on our 'Mind over matter' report. I'm very pleased to welcome Carol Shillabeer, who is chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, and who manages the Together for Children and Young People programme. Thank you very much for attending, and thank you for the written update that you provided in advance to the committee. We've got a lot of ground that we want to cover this morning, so if it's okay we'll go straight into questions. If I can just start and ask you if you're satisfied with the progress that's been made since the programme was established in 2015.&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Thank you very much for that question, Chair. I've got to say 'yes', in many regards. So, the key focus of" target="1. The Together for Children and Young People program, established in 2015, has made significant progress, particularly in building fundamental blocks for service improvement, collective audit, reflection, and learning from one another. This assessment comes from Carol Shillabeer, the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, who manages the program.&#10;2. The program has been guided by a report called 'Making Sense' from Hafal, which outlines 10 key asks from young people who had experience with the service. These asks focus on supporting teachers and others at an earlier stage, as well as ensuring that specialist help is available when needed.&#10;3. The program has also been involved in developing transition guidance for children moving from children's to adult services, although there is still work to be done to ensure a smooth transition and prevent young people from falling through the gaps.&#10;4. Additionally, the program aims to create a more integrated and joined-up approach between health and social care for approximately 100 children who have experienced care in multiple settings. This initiative involves bringing together social care and healthcare teams to provide better coordinated services for these vulnerable children, with a meeting scheduled with the Children's Commissioner to discuss next steps.&#10;5. The program intersects with the outcomes for the children in care work programme through cross-links such as having a member of the program board sitting on the outcomes for children ministerial group and having a director of social services on the program board. This ensures that there is clear communication between the two groups to better support vulnerable children and young people in Wales.">
