    <edge source="Based on the transcripts provided, it is not explicitly stated that there is a completely consistent service available for all young people in Wales when it comes to interventions during instances of self-harm. Lynne Neagle AM mentioned inconsistencies in crisis care, but she did state that the framework for improvement has strengthened over the past five years and has provided a vehicle for clinicians and professionals to come together.&#10;&#10;Carol Shillabeer acknowledged the issue of varying services across Wales and emphasized the need for a whole-system approach to children and young people's mental health, recognizing the importance of earlier progress on psychological therapies and support for looked-after children who have experienced challenging backgrounds. She did not explicitly confirm that a consistent service is available for all young people in Wales.&#10;&#10;In summary, while there have been efforts to improve children's mental health services in Wales and create more consistency, the transcripts do not definitively state that such consistency has been achieved across the country, particularly in relation to interventions during instances of self-harm." target="❓ Question: How is the Welsh social care system planning to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children within the next five to ten years, including reaching those in foster care with less frequent reviews, and can this be accomplished according to the confidence of Suzy Davies AM and Carol Shillabeer?&#10;&#10;The Welsh social care system plans to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children by focusing on the 'early help and enhanced support' work stream. This initiative will question whether a greater emphasis on emotional health and mental health should be incorporated into the health assessment of young people who are care experienced. Specifically, they aim to ensure that this aspect of support is more prominent and suitable for children with challenging backgrounds that led them to become part of the system.&#10;&#10;This enhanced focus on emotional and mental health assessments will address Suzy Davies AM's concern about reaching children who are being fostered and may not have frequent looked-after children reviews, ensuring that these interventions reach all relevant young people in various situations.&#10;&#10;Carol Shillabeer, as the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, did not explicitly express confidence in the plan but acknowledged the importance of this work and the need for a whole-system approach to children and young people's mental health. The Welsh social care system's top officials recognize the significance of these improvements, and they are working towards making earlier progress on psychological therapies and support for looked-after children.&#10;&#10;Considering the information provided in the transcripts, it is reasonable to suggest that there is a strong commitment from key figures like Suzy Davies AM and Carol Shillabeer to enhance emotional and mental health assessments for looked-after children within the next five to ten years, including reaching those in foster care with less frequent reviews.">
