    <edge source=" how the programme intersects, then, with the outcomes for the children in care work programme?&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer&#10;Content: Thanks very much for that. So, we have one of our members of the programme board also sitting on the outcomes for children ministerial group, which is good. So, we've got that cross-link. We also have a director of social services on our programme board and, obviously, they're very clearly linked in to the outcomes for children. I just made reference to, under the question on specialist CAMHS in-patients, the need to bring those services together, and that, really, is the need for much stronger working between the outcomes for children group and the Together for Children and Young People programme and the constituent parts. So, I'm confident that that has been pegged now. We've got a way forward and there is a consensus that we need to do things together on that.&#10;Speaker: Suzy Davies AM&#10;Content: Can you just perhaps give us an example of how that then looks on the ground? Because it's great that people are talking together, but how would that affect, I don't know, individual members of the workforce, or, indeed, the children we're talking" target="1. The Together for Children and Young People program, established in 2015, has made significant progress, particularly in building fundamental blocks for service improvement, collective audit, reflection, and learning from one another. This assessment comes from Carol Shillabeer, the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, who manages the program.&#10;2. The program has been guided by a report called 'Making Sense' from Hafal, which outlines 10 key asks from young people who had experience with the service. These asks focus on supporting teachers and others at an earlier stage, as well as ensuring that specialist help is available when needed.&#10;3. The program has also been involved in developing transition guidance for children moving from children's to adult services, although there is still work to be done to ensure a smooth transition and prevent young people from falling through the gaps.&#10;4. Additionally, the program aims to create a more integrated and joined-up approach between health and social care for approximately 100 children who have experienced care in multiple settings. This initiative involves bringing together social care and healthcare teams to provide better coordinated services for these vulnerable children, with a meeting scheduled with the Children's Commissioner to discuss next steps.&#10;5. The program intersects with the outcomes for the children in care work programme through cross-links such as having a member of the program board sitting on the outcomes for children ministerial group and having a director of social services on the program board. This ensures that there is clear communication between the two groups to better support vulnerable children and young people in Wales.">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source=" of the programme, we had a report from Hafal called 'Making Sense' and there were 10 key asks, if you like, of the system and the service from young people who had experience of the service. They said, 'Please don't medicalise it'—I'm paraphrasing now, of course—'Please don't medicalise it; please focus on supporting teachers and others who can support us at an earlier stage and then, when we really need help, please ensure that it is there at that more specialist level.' That's been a bit of a guiding principle for the programme. So, that reflects the questions that you were asking, really.&#10;Speaker: Janet Finch-Saunders AM&#10;Content: Thank you. What are the outcomes of the stakeholder workshop held last week on early help and enhanced support? And how are the actions going to be taken forward and implemented? And also, given that the Together for Children and Young People programme comes to an end in October of this year, who, in your view, is best placed to forward this work stream, and what will be the biggest challenges? It's a bit of a long question, so, break it up however you like.&#10;Speaker: Carol Shillabeer" target="1. Further development work on early help and enhanced support: Both the speakers recognize that there is still significant development work required for early help and enhanced support, which may take another year or 18 months to complete. This suggests that the current program has not yet fully addressed these critical areas, and further efforts are needed.&#10;   &#10;2. Evaluating the current program's effectiveness: While the current Together for Children and Young People program has made progress in certain areas, there have been lulls during its implementation. Given this, it is essential to assess whether extending the current program would be more beneficial or if a new multi-agency effort should take its place.&#10;&#10;3. Maintaining a holistic approach: It is crucial to maintain a comprehensive view of children's mental health by focusing on early help, enhanced support, and youth work. This integrated strategy ensures that all aspects affecting children's mental health are addressed, including interventions at critical stages in their lives.&#10;&#10;4. Role of regional partnership boards: Regional partnership boards play an essential role in facilitating collaboration between local authorities, health boards, and other key partners to effectively plan, commission, and deliver mental health services for children and young people. By working closely with these boards, the Together for Children and Young People program can promote best practices, support resource allocation, and monitor progress towards improving mental health outcomes.&#10;&#10;5. Establishing legacy arrangements: To sustain the gains achieved during the program, clear legacy arrangements must be established. Specialist CAMHS services will likely be integrated into the NHS mental health network, while the whole-school approach element has already been adopted by the government. The challenge lies in determining where early help and enhanced support fit within the system and ensuring a smooth transition for this work stream.&#10;&#10;Given these factors, it may be more appropriate to consider a different multi-agency effort that builds upon the progress made by the Together for Children and Young People program while addressing its identified gaps, particularly in early help and enhanced support. This new initiative should collaborate with regional partnership boards, maintain a holistic approach, and establish clear legacy arrangements to ensure long-term success.">
