    <edge source="Based on the transcript provided, Carol Shillabeer, the chief executive of Powys Teaching Health Board, expressed satisfaction with the progress made since establishing the Together for Children and Young People program in 2015, particularly in terms of building fundamental blocks for service improvement, collective audit, reflection, and learning from one another. However, she acknowledged that there is still more work to be done in creating an enabling environment for practitioners and staff. She also mentioned ongoing efforts to improve the provision of Welsh language services within the health board." target="The workforce profile in Wales is evolving to address recruitment challenges by implementing skill mixing. This approach involves using different types of roles, including those from the third sector, to provide direct front-line service provision. The trend shows a move towards better skill mix, with health boards like Powys Teaching Health Board employing more psychology assistants and other non-traditional professionals.&#10;&#10;The third sector is making significant contributions to service provision in various areas of healthcare services. This involvement is expected to continue and increase due to ongoing recruitment challenges and training time constraints for nursing and other professionals. While there has been an increase in commissioning numbers for nursing and other professionals, the shortage is not a quick fix, as it takes time for new recruits to receive training.&#10;&#10;In response to these challenges, healthcare services are focusing on staff retention, well-being, teamwork, culture of organizations, and career opportunities for healthcare professionals, in addition to traditional training and development efforts. Communities of practice have also become standard across healthcare services, allowing professionals to collaborate, reflect on service improvement, and learn from one another, which supports upskilling and developing the existing workforce by sharing best practices and knowledge.&#10;&#10;In summary, the trend in workforce profile shows a shift towards skill mixing, with the third sector playing an increasingly important role in service provision compared to NHS-employed professionals. This approach is expected to continue as healthcare services address recruitment challenges and focus on staff development and well-being.">
